The tar pipe idiom.

Once you are comfortable with tar, there is a pattern worth knowing for moving a whole directory tree from one place to another without ever creating an archive file on disk. It rests on one small trick: when you give tar a single dash where the filename would go, it reads from standard input or writes to standard output instead of a file.

That means you can pipe one tar straight into another. The first tar creates an archive of your source directory and writes it to standard output; the second tar reads that stream from standard input and extracts it into a destination directory. The bytes flow directly from one process to the other, and no archive file is ever written to disk in between.

The classic use of this is transferring a directory across the network over s-s-h. You create and compress on your side, the stream travels over the secure connection, and a tar on the far side decompresses and extracts it into place. There is no intermediate file and no double disk activity, which makes it efficient and clean.

For routine copy-this-directory-to-that-machine jobs you would usually reach for rsync, which is even better because it sends only the files that changed and can resume if interrupted. But the tar pipe is available everywhere, even on the most minimal systems, so it is a good trick to carry. The takeaway to remember is simply that a lone dash means use standard input or output instead of a file, and that one trick makes tar compose with the rest of the shell.
